INSERT INTO flashcards (course_id, question_text, answer_text, difficulty, order_index) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'How do Type 1, Type 2, LADA, and gestational diabetes differ?', 'Type 1: autoimmune destruction of beta cells, absolute insulin deficiency, usually young onset, requires insulin. Type 2: insulin resistance with relative deficiency, lifestyle and genetic factors, usually adults, managed with lifestyle/oral agents/insulin. LADA (Latent Autoimmune Diabetes in Adults): autoimmune like T1 but slower onset, initially appears as T2, eventually requires insulin. Gestational diabetes: hyperglycaemia first diagnosed in pregnancy, usually resolves postpartum but increases risk of T2 diabetes later.', 2, 26),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is the pathophysiology of Type 1 diabetes?', 'Type 1 diabetes is an autoimmune condition where T-lymphocytes attack and destroy pancreatic beta cells, which produce insulin. It is associated with autoantibodies (anti-GAD, anti-IA2, anti-islet cell, anti-insulin antibodies). Genetic susceptibility (HLA DR3/DR4) and environmental triggers (viral infections) are implicated. Destruction of beta cells leads to absolute insulin deficiency — without insulin, glucose cannot enter cells, leading to hyperglycaemia, ketogenesis, and if untreated, diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA).', 3, 27),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is the pathophysiology of Type 2 diabetes?', 'Type 2 diabetes involves two main defects: (1) Insulin resistance — target cells (liver, muscle, adipose) become less responsive to insulin, requiring higher insulin secretion to maintain normoglycaemia. (2) Relative insulin deficiency — beta cells cannot maintain sufficient insulin secretion to overcome resistance, resulting in hyperglycaemia. Contributing factors: obesity, physical inactivity, genetic predisposition, age, ethnicity, and excess caloric intake. Unlike T1, there is residual insulin secretion.', 2, 28),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What does HbA1c measure and what are the target ranges?', 'HbA1c (glycated haemoglobin) reflects average blood glucose over the preceding 2–3 months by measuring the proportion of haemoglobin with glucose attached. Diagnostic thresholds: ≥48 mmol/mol (6.5%) = diabetes; 42–47 mmol/mol = pre-diabetes. Treatment targets (NICE NG28): 48 mmol/mol for most T2 patients on lifestyle or metformin alone; 53 mmol/mol for patients on drugs causing hypoglycaemia (e.g. sulphonylureas, insulin) or with comorbidities. Higher targets (58–64) for frail elderly or those with hypoglycaemia unawareness.', 2, 29),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is the correct technique for capillary blood glucose monitoring?', 'Wash and dry hands (not alcohol wipes — affect reading). Lance the side of a fingertip (less painful than the pad). Apply a small drop of blood to the test strip without smearing. Read the glucose meter result. Document in the patient''s record. Rotate finger prick sites to prevent scarring and callus formation. Use appropriate blood glucose target ranges (fasting: 4–7 mmol/L; 2 hours post-meal: <8.5–9 mmol/L). Calibrate meters regularly and perform quality control checks per policy.', 1, 30),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'How does Continuous Glucose Monitoring (CGM) work?', 'CGM uses a sensor inserted subcutaneously (typically on the arm or abdomen) that measures interstitial fluid glucose every 1–5 minutes. It transmits readings to a receiver, smartphone, or insulin pump. CGM provides trend arrows showing whether glucose is rising, falling, or stable, enabling proactive management. Flash glucose monitoring (e.g. FreeStyle Libre) requires the sensor to be scanned. Real-time CGM provides continuous alerts. CGM is more accurate than intermittent finger-prick testing for detecting hypoglycaemia and reducing HbA1c.', 2, 31),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are the main types of insulin and when are they used?', 'Rapid-acting analogue (e.g. NovoRapid, Humalog): taken immediately before or after meals, peak 30–90 min. Short-acting (Actrapid): 30 min before meals, used in insulin infusions and DKA. Intermediate-acting (NPH, Insulatard): once or twice daily for basal coverage. Long-acting analogue (Lantus, Levemir): once or twice daily, peakless basal insulin. Mixed (Novomix 30): biphasic — used twice daily with meals. Basal-bolus regimen (long-acting + rapid-acting with meals) provides the most physiological control.', 2, 32),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is correct insulin injection technique and why is site rotation important?', 'Insulin is injected subcutaneously (SC). Sites: abdomen (fastest absorption), outer thigh (slower), outer upper arm, buttocks. Use appropriate pen needle length (4–6 mm for most adults). Inject at 90 degrees (or 45 degrees if thin). Do not massage after injection. Rotate sites systematically within each area to prevent lipohypertrophy — a complication of repeated injection into the same site causing lumpy SC tissue that alters insulin absorption unpredictably, leading to erratic blood glucose control.', 2, 33),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are the causes, symptoms, and BGL thresholds for hypoglycaemia?', 'Hypoglycaemia: blood glucose <4.0 mmol/L. Causes: excess insulin or sulphonylurea, missed/delayed meal, increased exercise, alcohol, renal impairment. Symptoms: adrenergic (sweating, tremor, palpitations, anxiety) then neuroglycopenic (confusion, drowsiness, slurred speech, seizure, coma). Level 1 hypo: BGL 3.0–3.9 mmol/L. Level 2: BGL <3.0 mmol/L. Level 3: severe — requiring assistance from another person. Treat promptly to prevent brain damage.', 2, 34),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is the 15-15 rule for treating hypoglycaemia?', 'For conscious patients with hypoglycaemia: (1) Give 15–20g fast-acting carbohydrate (e.g. 150–200 mL pure fruit juice, 5–6 glucose tablets, 4–5 jelly babies, Glucogel 2 tubes). (2) Wait 15 minutes and recheck blood glucose. (3) If still <4 mmol/L, repeat fast-acting carbohydrate. (4) Once BGL >4 mmol/L and patient is recovering, give a long-acting carbohydrate snack (biscuits, bread) to prevent recurrence. Document episode, treatment, and response. Investigate and address the cause.', 1, 35),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'How is severe hypoglycaemia managed and when is glucagon used?', 'Severe hypoglycaemia (unconscious, unable to swallow, level 3): do NOT give oral treatment (aspiration risk). Options: IV glucose 10% (100–200 mL over 15 minutes) via IV access (fastest, preferred in hospital). IM/SC glucagon 1 mg (GlucaGen or Baqsimi nasal powder) — stimulates hepatic glycogen breakdown; less effective in alcohol-intoxicated patients or prolonged hypoglycaemia (glycogen depleted). Recheck BGL, give long-acting carbohydrate once conscious. Hospitalise if recurrent or prolonged. Educate patient and family on prevention and emergency management.', 3, 36),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What causes hyperglycaemia in a person with diabetes and what are the symptoms?', 'Causes: insufficient insulin/medication, excessive carbohydrate intake, illness/infection (stress hormones increase BGL), reduced physical activity, steroid use, missed medication, new diagnosis. Symptoms: polyuria (excessive urination), polydipsia (excessive thirst), weight loss, fatigue, blurred vision, recurrent infections (thrush, UTI), and slow wound healing. BGL typically >11.1 mmol/L post-meal or >7.0 mmol/L fasting. Persistent hyperglycaemia damages blood vessels and nerves over time (complications). Treat the underlying cause and review medication.', 2, 37),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are the signs of DKA and how is it managed as an emergency?', 'DKA (diabetic ketoacidosis): predominantly Type 1. Signs: BGL >11 mmol/L (or known diabetes), ketonaemia ≥3 mmol/L or +++ ketonuria, pH <7.3 or bicarbonate <15 mmol/L. Clinical: nausea/vomiting, abdominal pain, Kussmaul breathing (deep, sighing), acetone breath, dehydration, reduced consciousness. Emergency management: IV fluid resuscitation (0.9% NaCl), insulin infusion (fixed rate per weight, FRIII), IV potassium replacement (hypokalaemia risk with insulin), monitor BGL and ketones hourly, treat precipitating cause.', 3, 38),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'How is Hyperosmolar Hyperglycaemic State (HHS) recognised and differentiated from DKA?', 'HHS: predominantly Type 2. BGL typically >30 mmol/L, marked dehydration, serum osmolality >320 mOsm/kg, no significant ketoacidosis (pH >7.3, bicarbonate >15 mmol/L). Clinical: gradual onset over days/weeks, profound dehydration, confusion, reduced GCS, absence of vomiting/acidosis. Differentiated from DKA: no significant ketosis, higher BGL, more severe dehydration, older patients. Management: slow careful rehydration (HHS patients are more profoundly dehydrated and at risk of osmotic complications), low-dose insulin, thromboembolism prophylaxis (high DVT risk), identify and treat precipitant.', 3, 39),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are sick day rules for people with diabetes?', 'Sick day rules advise people with diabetes what to do during illness (when BGL rises due to stress hormones and food intake may be erratic). Key principles: never stop insulin (even if not eating — may need more). Check BGL more frequently (every 2–4 hours). Check ketones (for T1 and insulin-treated T2). Maintain fluid intake. If unable to eat, replace meals with carbohydrate-containing drinks. Seek medical advice if: vomiting, BGL persistently >15 mmol/L, ketones >3 mmol/L, unwell more than 24–48 hours. SGLT2 inhibitors should be withheld during illness (DKA risk).', 2, 40),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is diabetic neuropathy and why is foot care important?', 'Diabetic neuropathy affects 50% of people with long-standing diabetes. Peripheral neuropathy causes sensory loss (inability to feel pain, pressure, temperature in feet), motor neuropathy (foot deformity), and autonomic neuropathy (reduced sweating, dry skin, arteriovenous shunting). Sensory loss means injuries (cuts, blisters, pressure sores) may go unnoticed. Combined with ischaemia from peripheral arterial disease, this leads to diabetic foot ulcers, infection, osteomyelitis, and amputation. Annual diabetic foot checks and patient education on daily foot inspection are essential.', 2, 41),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are the perioperative considerations for a person with diabetes undergoing surgery?', 'Perioperative management: assess type of diabetes and usual medication. Variable rate IV insulin infusion (VRIII/sliding scale) is used for most insulin-treated T2 and T1 patients undergoing major surgery or prolonged nil-by-mouth. Oral agents (especially metformin) are typically withheld on the day of surgery and restarted when eating. Aim for BGL 6–10 mmol/L perioperatively. Check BGL hourly during surgery. SGLT2 inhibitors should be withheld 3 days before surgery. Good perioperative glucose control reduces surgical site infection, length of stay, and mortality.', 3, 42),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are SGLT2 inhibitors and GLP-1 agonists and how do they work?', 'SGLT2 inhibitors (e.g. empagliflozin, dapagliflozin, canagliflozin): block sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 in the kidney, causing glucose excretion in urine. Benefit beyond glucose lowering: cardioprotection and renoprotection. Risk: euglycaemic DKA, genital thrush. Withheld during illness and surgery. GLP-1 receptor agonists (e.g. semaglutide/Ozempic, liraglutide/Victoza): mimic GLP-1 (incretin), stimulating glucose-dependent insulin secretion, suppressing glucagon, slowing gastric emptying, and reducing appetite. Significant weight loss and cardiovascular benefit. Injectable or oral. Risk: nausea, pancreatitis.', 3, 43),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are the microvascular and macrovascular complications of diabetes?', 'Microvascular (small vessel): diabetic retinopathy (leading cause of blindness in working-age adults), diabetic nephropathy (leading cause of end-stage renal disease), diabetic peripheral neuropathy. All related to chronic hyperglycaemia causing endothelial damage. Macrovascular (large vessel): accelerated atherosclerosis leading to coronary artery disease (MI), cerebrovascular disease (stroke), and peripheral arterial disease (amputation). Macrovascular disease is the leading cause of mortality in T2 diabetes. Optimal HbA1c, BP, and lipid control reduces complication risk.', 2, 44),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'How does diabetes interact with renal failure?', 'Diabetic nephropathy is the most common cause of end-stage renal disease in the UK. Renal impairment affects diabetes management: metformin is contraindicated when eGFR <30 (risk of lactic acidosis). SGLT2 inhibitors lose efficacy and some are contraindicated at low eGFR. Insulin clearance is reduced — dose reduction required to prevent hypoglycaemia. Sulphonylureas accumulate (hypoglycaemia risk). HbA1c may be unreliable in renal anaemia (altered red cell turnover). CGM or self-monitoring of blood glucose (SMBG) is preferred for monitoring. Frequent medication review is essential.', 3, 45),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are the specific challenges of diabetes management in older adults with frailty?', 'In frail older adults: HbA1c targets are relaxed (58–64 mmol/mol or individualised) to avoid hypoglycaemia. Hypoglycaemia causes falls, fractures, confusion, and cardiovascular events in this group. SGLT2 inhibitors may cause falls (volume depletion), urinary tract infections, and perineal infections. Insulin regimens should be simplified. Cognitive impairment affects self-management. Regular medication review using STOPP/START criteria. Assess hypoglycaemia awareness (hypoglycaemia unawareness is more common in long-standing diabetes). Involve carers and community teams in management.', 3, 46),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are the DESMOND and DAFNE structured education programmes?', 'DESMOND (Diabetes Education and Self-Management for Ongoing and Newly Diagnosed): a group-based structured education programme for people with Type 2 diabetes. Covers: understanding diabetes, lifestyle change, medication, monitoring, and complication prevention. DAFNE (Dose Adjustment For Normal Eating): a structured intensive programme for people with Type 1 diabetes, teaching carbohydrate counting and flexible insulin dose adjustment to achieve better glycaemic control while maintaining a normal diet and lifestyle. Both are NICE-recommended and evidence-based. Referral is recommended at diagnosis.', 1, 47),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What are the key elements of diabetes care planning in care homes?', 'People with diabetes in care homes are at high risk of hypoglycaemia, undetected hyperglycaemia, and poor foot health. Care planning must include: individualised HbA1c and BGL targets (avoid over-treatment in frail residents), insulin management protocols and training for care home staff, hypoglycaemia recognition and treatment protocol, foot care plan with annual review, medication review (deprescribing where appropriate), dietary support, and regular GP/specialist review. Joint working with community diabetic nurses and GPs is essential. Document residents'' capacity and preferences.', 2, 48),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is diabetes distress and how should it be addressed?', 'Diabetes distress is the negative emotional impact of living with diabetes — fear of complications, burden of self-management, frustration with glucose variability, anxiety about hypoglycaemia, and social stigma. It is distinct from clinical depression but may coexist. It is associated with poor glycaemic control, reduced self-care, and worse outcomes. Assessment tools: Problem Areas In Diabetes (PAID) scale. Management: validate the patient''s experience, offer peer support, psychology referral, structured education, and review of treatment burden (simplify regimen where possible). Ask about emotional wellbeing at every consultation.', 2, 49),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What does NICE guideline NG28 recommend for Type 2 diabetes management?', 'NICE NG28 (Type 2 diabetes in adults, updated 2022) recommends: lifestyle intervention (diet, exercise, weight loss) as first-line. If HbA1c not at target: add metformin (unless contraindicated). Second-line: consider SGLT2 inhibitor (particularly for those with cardiovascular disease, heart failure, or renal disease) or DPP-4 inhibitor or sulphonylurea. GLP-1 agonist if BMI ≥35 or specific comorbidity. Insulin when other agents insufficient. HbA1c target 48 mmol/mol (or 53 if hypoglycaemia risk). Annual review of all complications. Shared decision-making in all treatment choices.', 3, 50)
INSERT INTO quiz_questions (course_id, question_text, option_a, option_b, option_c, option_d, correct_option, explanation) VALUES
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'Which autoimmune antibodies are associated with Type 1 diabetes?', 'Anti-thyroid peroxidase and anti-TSH receptor antibodies', 'Anti-GAD, anti-IA2, and anti-islet cell antibodies', 'Anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibodies (ANCA)', 'Anti-dsDNA and anti-Smith antibodies', 'B', 'Type 1 diabetes is associated with autoantibodies against islet cell antigens including anti-GAD (glutamic acid decarboxylase), anti-IA2 (islet antigen 2), anti-insulin antibodies, and anti-islet cell antibodies. These markers indicate autoimmune beta cell destruction and can help differentiate Type 1 from Type 2 or LADA.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What HbA1c value confirms a diagnosis of diabetes?', '≥42 mmol/mol (6.0%)', '≥48 mmol/mol (6.5%)', '≥53 mmol/mol (7.0%)', '≥58 mmol/mol (7.5%)', 'B', 'An HbA1c of ≥48 mmol/mol (6.5%) on two occasions confirms a diagnosis of diabetes (one occasion if symptomatic). An HbA1c of 42–47 mmol/mol indicates pre-diabetes (high risk). HbA1c is preferred over fasting glucose for diagnosing Type 2 diabetes in asymptomatic individuals in the UK, as recommended by NICE and WHO.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'A conscious adult patient with Type 1 diabetes has a blood glucose of 2.8 mmol/L and is pale and sweating. What is the correct immediate treatment?', 'Administer IM glucagon 1 mg immediately', 'Give 15–20g fast-acting carbohydrate (e.g. 150 mL fruit juice or 5 glucose tablets) and recheck BGL in 15 minutes', 'Administer IV 50% glucose immediately', 'Give a mixed carbohydrate meal', 'B', 'For a conscious hypoglycaemic patient who can swallow safely, the correct treatment is 15–20g of fast-acting carbohydrate (15-15 rule). Recheck BGL after 15 minutes and repeat if still <4 mmol/L. IM glucagon and IV glucose are reserved for patients who are unconscious or unable to swallow.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'A patient with Type 1 diabetes presents with BGL of 22 mmol/L, ketonaemia of 4 mmol/L, and pH of 7.22. What is the likely diagnosis?', 'Hyperosmolar Hyperglycaemic State (HHS)', 'Diabetic Ketoacidosis (DKA)', 'Reactive hypoglycaemia', 'Type 2 diabetes newly diagnosed', 'B', 'DKA is characterised by hyperglycaemia (typically >11 mmol/L), ketonaemia (≥3 mmol/L or significant ketonuria), and acidosis (pH <7.3 or bicarbonate <15 mmol/L). This presentation meets all three criteria. HHS has much higher BGL (>30 mmol/L), no significant ketoacidosis, and occurs predominantly in Type 2 diabetes.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'Which insulin type is most appropriate for once-daily basal insulin in Type 2 diabetes?', 'Rapid-acting insulin aspart', 'Short-acting Actrapid', 'NPH (intermediate-acting) insulin', 'Long-acting insulin glargine (Lantus)', 'D', 'Long-acting insulin analogues such as insulin glargine (Lantus) or insulin detemir (Levemir) are used for once-daily (or twice-daily) basal insulin. They have a peakless profile lasting 18–24+ hours, providing stable background insulin coverage and less nocturnal hypoglycaemia risk compared to NPH insulin.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'A patient with diabetes attends a routine foot check and is found to have absent vibration sensation bilaterally with intact skin. What is this an early sign of?', 'Peripheral arterial disease', 'Diabetic peripheral neuropathy', 'Cellulitis', 'Venous insufficiency', 'B', 'Absent vibration sensation (tested with a 128 Hz tuning fork) bilaterally is an early sign of diabetic peripheral neuropathy. This reduces the patient''s ability to perceive pain and injury, placing them at high risk of undetected foot ulcers. Annual foot checks and patient education on daily foot inspection are recommended by NICE.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is the key advice for a patient with Type 1 diabetes during an intercurrent illness (sick day rules)?', 'Stop insulin as the patient is not eating enough to need it', 'Continue or increase insulin as illness increases BGL via stress hormones; check BGL and ketones every 2–4 hours', 'Switch to oral glucose tablets only', 'Attend A&E immediately regardless of BGL', 'B', 'Sick day rules for Type 1 diabetes: never stop insulin — illness raises BGL through stress hormone release. Insulin requirements often increase during illness. Monitor BGL and ketones every 2–4 hours. Maintain hydration with carbohydrate-containing fluids if not eating. Seek urgent medical advice if vomiting, ketones >3 mmol/L, or BGL uncontrolled. Stopping insulin during illness can precipitate DKA.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'How does CGM (continuous glucose monitoring) improve diabetes self-management compared to finger-prick testing?', 'CGM is less accurate than finger-prick testing but more convenient', 'CGM provides real-time glucose trends and hypoglycaemia alerts, allowing proactive rather than reactive glucose management', 'CGM is only suitable for Type 2 diabetes patients', 'CGM replaces the need for HbA1c monitoring', 'B', 'CGM provides continuous glucose readings with trend arrows showing direction and rate of change, enabling proactive dose adjustments. It significantly improves hypoglycaemia detection (especially nocturnal) and time-in-range. Evidence shows CGM reduces HbA1c and hypoglycaemic episodes in Type 1 diabetes and selected Type 2 patients. It supplements but does not fully replace HbA1c monitoring.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'Which of the following BEST describes the mechanism of action of SGLT2 inhibitors?', 'They stimulate insulin secretion from pancreatic beta cells', 'They block sodium-glucose co-transporter 2 in the kidney, causing urinary glucose excretion', 'They sensitise peripheral tissues to insulin action', 'They inhibit glucagon secretion from pancreatic alpha cells', 'B', 'SGLT2 inhibitors (e.g. empagliflozin, dapagliflozin) block the SGLT2 transporter in the proximal renal tubule, preventing reabsorption of filtered glucose and causing glucose to be excreted in urine (glycosuria). This lowers blood glucose without stimulating insulin. They also have significant cardioprotective and renoprotective benefits independent of glucose lowering.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'Why are relaxed HbA1c targets used for frail older adults with diabetes?', 'Because HbA1c is not a reliable test in older adults', 'To prevent hypoglycaemia which in frail older adults causes falls, fractures, confusion, and cardiovascular events', 'Because older adults do not develop complications from hyperglycaemia', 'Because metformin cannot be used in older adults', 'B', 'Tight glycaemic control in frail older adults carries a high risk of hypoglycaemia, which can cause falls, hip fractures, delirium, and cardiovascular events — all of which carry significant morbidity and mortality in this population. Relaxed HbA1c targets (58–64 mmol/mol, or individualised) balance the benefit of avoiding complications against the immediate risk of hypoglycaemia.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is lipohypertrophy and what are its clinical implications?', 'Fat atrophy caused by insulin pump infusion sets', 'Lumpy subcutaneous fatty tissue caused by repeated insulin injections into the same site, leading to erratic insulin absorption', 'A complication of insulin allergy', 'Subcutaneous infection at the injection site', 'B', 'Lipohypertrophy is caused by repeated injection into the same site, stimulating localised fat cell hypertrophy. Insulin absorbed from lipohypertrophic tissue is less predictable — it may be absorbed more slowly, then released erratically, causing unexplained BGL fluctuations. Patients should be taught to rotate injection sites systematically across the recommended areas to prevent this complication.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What is the primary macrovascular complication responsible for the majority of deaths in Type 2 diabetes?', 'Diabetic retinopathy', 'Diabetic nephropathy', 'Coronary artery disease', 'Peripheral neuropathy', 'C', 'Macrovascular disease (accelerated atherosclerosis) is the leading cause of mortality in Type 2 diabetes. Coronary artery disease (myocardial infarction) accounts for the majority of diabetes-related deaths. People with T2 diabetes have 2–4 times the risk of cardiovascular disease compared to the general population. This is why NICE recommends early use of SGLT2 inhibitors and statins, alongside glycaemic control, for cardiovascular risk reduction.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'When is metformin contraindicated due to risk of lactic acidosis?', 'eGFR <60 mL/min/1.73m²', 'eGFR <45 mL/min/1.73m²', 'eGFR <30 mL/min/1.73m²', 'eGFR <50 mL/min/1.73m²', 'C', 'Metformin is contraindicated when eGFR is <30 mL/min/1.73m² due to the risk of lactic acidosis from metformin accumulation in severe renal impairment. The dose should be reviewed at eGFR <45 and metformin should generally be used with caution between eGFR 30–45. It should also be withheld perioperatively, during IV contrast studies, and in severe dehydration or illness.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'What structured education programme is NICE-recommended for people with Type 1 diabetes who want to learn flexible insulin dosing?', 'DESMOND', 'DAFNE (Dose Adjustment For Normal Eating)', 'EXPERT patient programme', 'LOOK AHEAD trial programme', 'B', 'DAFNE (Dose Adjustment For Normal Eating) is a NICE-recommended, evidence-based structured education programme for people with Type 1 diabetes. It teaches carbohydrate counting and flexible insulin dose adjustment, allowing participants to eat a normal varied diet while achieving improved glycaemic control. Studies show DAFNE significantly reduces HbA1c and improves quality of life.'),
('10000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000028', 'Which SGLT2 inhibitor-related adverse effect requires withholding the medication 3 days before elective surgery?', 'Renal impairment', 'Euglycaemic diabetic ketoacidosis', 'Genital thrush', 'Urinary tract infection', 'B', 'SGLT2 inhibitors can cause euglycaemic DKA — a form of DKA where BGL may be only mildly elevated (not >11 mmol/L), making it easy to miss. Surgical stress, fasting, and carbohydrate restriction increase the risk. SGLT2 inhibitors should be withheld 3 days before planned surgery (per JBDS guidelines) and during acute illness to prevent this serious complication.')
